  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation combating money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, US)\n- First international anti-money laundering guidelines\n- Limited regulatory frameworks\n\n2. 1980s-1990s Developments\n- FATF (Financial Action Task Force) establishment\n- Enhanced international cooperation\n- More comprehensive reporting requirements\n- Criminalization of money laundering\n- Expanded financial institution responsibilities\n\n3. Post-9/11 Legislation\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Increased focus on terrorist financing\n- Stricter customer identification protocols\n- Enhanced information sharing mechanisms\n\n4. Recent Trends\n- Digital currency regulations\n- Cryptocurrency tracking\n- Enhanced beneficial ownership transparency\n- Expanded Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Risk-based compliance approaches\n- Stronger international enforcement mechanisms\n\n5. Emerging Technologies\n- AI-powered transaction monitoring\n- Blockchain traceability\n- Machine learning detection systems\n- Real-time compliance screening\n\n6. Global Regulatory Convergence\n- Standardized international compliance frameworks\n- Consistent cross-border enforcement approaches\n- Collaborative investigative techniques\n\nThe landscape continues evolving with technological advancements and emerging financial platforms.",
